gft.api
Interface Session

All Superinterfaces:
AccountEventsProvider, MessageEventsProvider, Messaging, OrderEventsProvider, Pricing, QuoteEventsProvider, SessionEventsProvider, Trading, UserSupport
public interface Session
extends SessionEventsProvider, Pricing, Trading, UserSupport, Messaging

A session is an entry point in using GFT API.

Session life-cycle.

In order to use GFT API, user must start new session: see start(gft.api.LoginRequest). If the session has been successfully started, isActive() call returns true. In order to close a session, user must explicitly call close(). Session cannot be restarted if it was previously closed.

Session usage.

Before using the session user should associate a SessionStateListener with it. This listener is called when a session becomes invalid for some reason. Making calls to invalidated session will result in java.lang.IllegalStateException.

In order to let a user perform business operations, session exposes a set of business interfaces:

  • Pricing
  • Trading
  • UserSupport
  • Messaging
Appropriate getters are provided for accessing these interfaces:
  • getPricing()
  • getTrading()
  • getUserSupport()
  • getMessaging()
Session implementation and all business API's accessible through it can be safely used from within multiple threads.

Author:
Boris Malkin

start

LoginContext start(LoginRequest loginRequest)
                   throws VersionException,
                          LoginException,
                          java.rmi.RemoteException
Starts this session. A session can be started once only. As soon as the session is closed explicitly by the close() method or invalidated due to connectivity or other problems, it cannot be re-started anymore. New session object must be created for that.

Parameters:
loginRequest - user's login request
Returns:
LoginContext object containing session-related information
Throws:
VersionException - in case of client-server compatibility problems.
LoginException - if login failed for some reason
java.rmi.RemoteException - in case of remote errors
java.lang.IllegalStateException - if start method was previously called already.
